== Sales ==
Analysts estimate Apple sold between 14 million and 16 million AirPods in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2018/12/12/how-big-can-apples-airpods-business-become/|title=How Big Can Apple's AirPods Business Become?|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315023751/https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2018/12/12/how-big-can-apples-airpods-business-become/|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, AirPods were Apple's most popular [[IPhone accessories|accessory product]], with 35 million units sold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobilesyrup.com/2018/12/03/apple-updated-airpods-release-2019/|title=Apple's updated AirPods will release in 2019: report|date=December 3, 2018|website=MobileSyrup|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=May 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518124920/https://mobilesyrup.com/2018/12/03/apple-updated-airpods-release-2019/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/19/03/15/apple-sold-35-million-airpods-in-2018-currently-most-popular-hearable-brand|title=Apple sold 35 million AirPods in 2018, currently most popular 'hearable' brand|last1=Fingas|first1=Roger|website=AppleInsider|date=March 15, 2019 |language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=April 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401085101/https://appleinsider.com/articles/19/03/15/apple-sold-35-million-airpods-in-2018-currently-most-popular-hearable-brand|url-status=live}}</ref> 60 million units were sold in 2019.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/apple-sold-nearly-60-million-airpods-in-2019-strategy-analytics-2020-1|title=Apple sold nearly 60 million AirPods in 2019, analysts estimate|last=Wood|first=Charlie|website=Business Insider|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=April 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406210553/https://www.businessinsider.com/apple-sold-nearly-60-million-airpods-in-2019-strategy-analytics-2020-1|url-status=live}}</ref> Analysts estimate AirPods make up 60% of the global wireless headphone market and that Apple's entire Wearables products (Apple Watch, AirPods, and AirPods Pro) "is now bigger than 60% of the companies in the [[Fortune 500]]".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/08/06/apple-airpods-business/|title=Apple's AirPods Business Is Bigger Than You Think|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303232826/https://fortune.com/2019/08/06/apple-airpods-business/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/09/10/apple-still-dominates-the-hearables-market.aspx|title=Apple Still Dominates the Hearables Market|last=CFA|first=Evan Niu|date=September 10, 2019|website=The Motley Fool|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305022010/https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/09/10/apple-still-dominates-the-hearables-market.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":5" /> An estimated 5-7% of Apple's revenue from AirPods comes from replacement earbuds and cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/apple-airpods-are-so-beloved-people-spend-more-than-half-a-billion-replacing-them/|title=People love AirPods so much they spend more than half a billion a year replacing them|website=CBS News|date=September 6, 2019 |language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=February 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221075656/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/apple-airpods-are-so-beloved-people-spend-more-than-half-a-billion-replacing-them/|url-status=live}}</ref> Analysts estimate Apple sold approximately 120 million pairs in 2021.<ref name="Businessweek cultural impact">{{cite news |last1=Chafkin |first1=Max |title=The Sneaky Genius of Apple's AirPods Empire |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2022-09-22/apple-airpods-sales-bode-well-for-vr-headset |access-date=September 25, 2022 |work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |date=September 22, 2022 |archive-date=September 30, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220930081755/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2022-09-22/apple-airpods-sales-bode-well-for-vr-headset |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Cultural impact ==
On announcement day, AirPods were compared to Apple's previously existing [[Apple earbuds|EarPods]] (2012–present), with ''[[The Verge]]'' noting "They look... just like the old EarPods, with the wires cut off."<ref>{{Cite web|last=Patel|first=Nilay|date=September 7, 2016|title=Apple AirPods hands (and ears) on|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/7/12838810/apple-airpods-wireless-headphones-hands-on-first-look|access-date=April 2, 2020|website=The Verge|language=en|archive-date=May 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504011445/https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/7/12838810/apple-airpods-wireless-headphones-hands-on-first-look|url-status=live}}</ref> Initially mocked by many for their unfamiliar design (including [[CNN]] asking "Would people actually wear these?" in 2016),<ref>{{Cite web|last=Kelly|first=Samantha Murphy|date=December 21, 2016|title=Apple AirPods review: Do they actually stay in your ears?|url=https://money.cnn.com/2016/12/21/technology/apple-airpods-review/index.html|access-date=April 2, 2020|website=CNNMoney|archive-date=April 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429134023/https://money.cnn.com/2016/12/21/technology/apple-airpods-review/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref> their popularity grew rapidly over the years and they were voted the most popular "hearable" brand of 2019.<ref name=":0" />

At an Apple earnings call in 2019, CEO [[Tim Cook]] called AirPods "nothing less than a cultural phenomenon".<ref>{{Cite web|last=Miller|first=Chance|date=April 30, 2019|title=Apple working to increase AirPods supply|url=https://9to5mac.com/2019/04/30/airpods-supply-demand-q2-2019/|access-date=April 2, 2020|website=9to5Mac|language=en-US|archive-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315042111/https://9to5mac.com/2019/04/30/airpods-supply-demand-q2-2019/|url-status=live}}</ref> AirPods had become a viral sensation with [[memes]] circulating across the internet about its appearance and its relation to the removal of the headphone jack in iPhones.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guynn |first1=Jessica |title=Don't lose your cool: Apple will help you find your errant AirPods |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/01/24/apple-find-my-airpods/97003084/ |access-date=May 3, 2021 |work=USA Today |date=January 24, 2017 |archive-date=May 3, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503143640/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/talkingtech/2017/01/24/apple-find-my-airpods/97003084/ |url-status=live }}</ref> However, as time wore on, AirPods became known as a status symbol.<ref name="Businessweek cultural impact"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Jacob |title=Do AirPods Make You Look Rich? These Millennials Think So |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/do-airpods-make-you-look-rich-these-millennials-think-so-11550591284 |access-date=May 3, 2021 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=February 19, 2019 |archive-date=May 3, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503151108/https://www.wsj.com/articles/do-airpods-make-you-look-rich-these-millennials-think-so-11550591284 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=How Apple's AirPods became a 'flex' — and why it matters|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/apple-s-airpods-once-punchline-emerge-flex-financial-force-n970541|access-date=April 2, 2020|website=NBC News|date=February 13, 2019 |language=en|archive-date=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317043932/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/apple-s-airpods-once-punchline-emerge-flex-financial-force-n970541|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Criticism ===
AirPods have been criticized for their high price; however, at launch they were actually priced less than most "[[True Wireless Headphones|true wireless]]" earbuds on the market (e.g. the Samsung Gear IconX and Bragi Dash) and remain competitively priced with similar products from other major brands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.google.com/product/pixel_buds|title=Pixel Buds|website=Google Store|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402205413/https://store.google.com/product/pixel_buds|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/28/16381800/samsung-gear-iconx-sale-original-model|title=Samsung's truly wireless earbuds are on sale for $50|last=Kastrenakes|first=Jacob|date=September 28, 2017|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=May 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200514063141/https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/28/16381800/samsung-gear-iconx-sale-original-model|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/5/12798640/bragi-wireless-headphones-earbuds-price-release-date|title=Bragi's new wireless earbuds are simpler and a lot cheaper|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=September 5, 2016|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=May 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200515163247/https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/5/12798640/bragi-wireless-headphones-earbuds-price-release-date|url-status=live}}</ref>

Since AirPods can easily be worn for long periods of time, AirPods have also had an effect on how people interact with each other. Having earphones in is generally perceived as a "do not disturb" signal, and some AirPods users use this fact to strategically avoid awkward small talk.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dolan|first=Rebecca|date=August 23, 2018|title=Sorry, Pal, I Don't Want to Talk: The Other Reason People Wear AirPods|language=en-US|work=Wall Street Journal|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorry-pal-i-dont-want-to-talk-the-other-reason-people-wear-airpods-1534949793|access-date=April 2, 2020|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> But in the collaborative workplace, constant use of AirPods has sometimes been interpreted as a sign of disrespect to co-workers, causing conflict in the office.<ref>{{Cite web|date=June 11, 2019|title='A totally different phenomenon': Airpods are changing agency office life|url=https://digiday.com/marketing/totally-different-phenomenon-airpods-changing-agency-office-life/|access-date=April 2, 2020|website=Digiday|language=en-US}}</ref>

Another prominent criticism was a problem that caused the charging case battery to deplete at a rapid rate despite the AirPods not being used. Users were reporting upwards of 30% idle discharge per day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/airpods-users-complain-battery-drainage-issues-charging-case/|title=AirPods Users Complain Of Charging Case Battery Drain Issues|date=December 28, 2016|website=Digital Trends|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=July 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200725010341/https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/airpods-users-complain-battery-drainage-issues-charging-case/|url-status=live}}</ref> In response, Apple released a firmware update (version 3.5.1) for the AirPods, which addressed connectivity and battery drain problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/02/01/apple-airpods-silently-receive-bug-fix-firmware-update-to-version-3-5-1/|title=Apple AirPods silently receive bug fix firmware update to version 3.5.1|last=Mayo|first=Benjamin|date=February 1, 2017|website=9to5Mac|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=February 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207113248/https://9to5mac.com/2017/02/01/apple-airpods-silently-receive-bug-fix-firmware-update-to-version-3-5-1/|url-status=live}}</ref> Students and college professors from the [[George Washington University]] have commented that AirPods have decreased students' daily social interactions.<ref>{{Cite web|date=February 19, 2019|title=Students, professors say AirPods make students less social|url=https://www.gwhatchet.com/2019/02/19/tuned-out-students-professors-say-airpods-limit-students-social-interactions/|access-date=April 2, 2020|website=The GW Hatchet}}</ref>

According to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', AirPods are difficult if not impossible to recycle, and not designed to be repairable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ig.ft.com/fixing-my-broken-wireless-earbuds/|title=I tried to fix my wireless earbuds. It did not go well|work=Financial Times|url-access=subscription|access-date=February 13, 2022|archive-date=March 14, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230314173700/https://www.ft.com/products?location=https%3A%2F%2F%2Ffixing-my-broken-wireless-earbuds%2F|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Replacement for hearing aids===
In 2022, researchers at the [[Taipei Veterans General Hospital]] in [[Taiwan]] compared the performance of AirPods 2 and the original AirPods Pro using [[Live Listen]] on an iPhone or iPad to compare to medical hearing aids. [[Oticon]] Opn 1 was the high-end comparison, with [[Bernafon]] MD1 as the more affordable alternative. The performance of the systems was at least assisting participants with Pro (including noise canceling features) being better and approximating the hearing aids.<ref name="2022-11-15_iS">[https://www.cell.com/iscience/fulltext/S2589-0042(22)01708-4 Smartphone-bundled earphones as personal sound amplification products in adults with sensorineural hearing loss] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221117085342/https://www.cell.com/iscience/fulltext/S2589-0042(22)01708-4 |date=November 17, 2022 }}, Heng-Yu Haley Lin et al, iScience, November 15, 2022</ref>

== Competition ==
Some consumers expressed the viewpoint that there were better options for wireless earphones based on quality and cost.<ref name=":8">{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/shop/select-airpods|title=Shop AirPods|website=Apple|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403173316/https://www.apple.com/shop/select-airpods|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://moneyinc.com/why-are-airpods-so-expensive/|title=Why Are AirPods So Expensive? Here's Why They're Overpriced|last=Flynn|first=Liz|date=October 12, 2019|website=Money Inc|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=February 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201042701/https://moneyinc.com/why-are-airpods-so-expensive/|url-status=live}}</ref> One of Apple's biggest competitors is [[Samsung]], which markets wireless earbuds that are very similar to AirPods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesdigitalcovers/2020/03/13/samsung-vs-apple-inside-the-brutal-war-for-smartphone-dominance/|title=Samsung vs. Apple: Inside The Brutal War For Smartphone Dominance|last=Cain|first=Geoffrey|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402163712/https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesdigitalcovers/2020/03/13/samsung-vs-apple-inside-the-brutal-war-for-smartphone-dominance/|url-status=live}}</ref> Another similar product line is from Apple's [[Beats Electronics]], which sells products such as the [[Powerbeats Pro]] wireless earbuds.<ref name=":9">{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatsbydre.com/earphones/powerbeats-pro|title=Powerbeats Pro|website=Beats by Dre|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020|archive-date=April 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422155654/https://www.beatsbydre.com/earphones/powerbeats-pro|url-status=live}}</ref>

